3tz.title: GalCom
3tz.text:
[summary: In the GalCom thought experiment, humanity is an inter-stellar situation and you make money on the stock market by living in one star system and sending information to an automated trader that you built in another star system. Sending interstellar information is possible, but very expensive — and you have a lot of data to send. Your profit margins are directly proportional to how efficiently you can transfer information between star systems. To send a signal, you have to reserve bits in advance. That means that you have to pick a set of messages and buy enough bits to cover the longest message that you might want to send. If you end up sending a shorter message you can sell some of the bits back. You send a very high volume of bits, so small decreases in the expected cost of sending information are worth a lot of effort.]

_The GalCom hypothetical is a thought experiment where sending a bit of information is a clearly defined and very expensive action, which makes it a useful thought experiment for various concepts in [-3qq] and [-1bv]._

The year is 21026. Humanity has become a flourishing inter-stellar civilization. Capitalism never died, and stock markets are thriving in various star systems. Due to the light-speed limitations, the markets are out of sync, and there's a lot of money to be made by setting up an automated trader in one star system, moving to another star system, and sending information about stock prices (and so on) to your automated trader the moment that information becomes known.

You set up your own automated trader in the Vega star system, and you currently make a living by transmitting market data from the Deneb star system. To transmit that data, you use the GalCom deep-space communications network.

You make a comfortable living, but you have a lot of data to transmit, and sending information on GalCom isn't cheap. Fortunately, it _is_ efficient: GalCom is a highly optimized network used by trillions of citizens to send and receive pulses of light across the cosmos. To send information via GalCom, you have to purchase [3p0 bits] of information. For each bit you purchase, you are allowed to control a single pulse in the GalCom signal, making it either be present (representing a 1) or absent (representing a 0).

You can buy bits at the last minute, but then there might be a long wait time until the bits are actually transmitted, which is a non-starter for your trading business — sending the information only makes you rich if you're literally the first person to send the information. However, GalCom also allows you to reserve bits, if you know when you're going to want to send them (i.e., just after a company's quarterly earnings come out). In this case, you have to pick a set of messages that you might send in advance, and then pay upfront for the longest message in that set. Fortunately, there's a secondary market on bits, so if you end up sending one of the shorter messages, you can resell some of those bits.

For example, say you know that you're going to send one of the following messages: "buy", "sell", or "hold". Naively, GalCom would require you to purchase 4 bytes of information (enough to transmit four letters), and then if you actually end up transmitting "buy" you can sell the last byte back (because you only used 3 of the 4).

Of course, you can send that message using much less than 4 bytes, if you're clever. Bits don't come cheap, and while you're able to make quite a bit of money off of your automated trader in the Vega system, your profit margins depend on you finding ways to transmit information as efficiently as possible. To do that, you can use [-3qq].
